<Link id="l00432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="432"><span class="doxyHighlight">      </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordFlow">if</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> (CondL == CondR &amp;&amp; LHSA == RHSA &amp;&amp; LHSB == RHSB)</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="434"><span class="doxyHighlight">    &#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00435" /><CodeLine lineNumber="435"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00436" /><CodeLine lineNumber="436"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// If the true/false operands are swapped and the conditions are compares</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00437" /><CodeLine lineNumber="437"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// with inverted predicates, the selects are equal:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00438" /><CodeLine lineNumber="438"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// select (icmp Pred, X, Y), A, B &lt;--&gt; select (icmp InvPred, X, Y), B, A</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00439" /><CodeLine lineNumber="439"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00440" /><CodeLine lineNumber="440"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This also handles patterns with a double-negation in the sense of not +</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00441" /><CodeLine lineNumber="441"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// inverse, because we looked through a &#39;not&#39; in the matching function and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00442" /><CodeLine lineNumber="442"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// swapped A/B:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00443" /><CodeLine lineNumber="443"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// select (cmp Pred, X, Y), A, B &lt;--&gt; select (not (cmp InvPred, X, Y)), B, A</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00444" /><CodeLine lineNumber="444"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00445" /><CodeLine lineNumber="445"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This intentionally does NOT handle patterns with a double-negation in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00446" /><CodeLine lineNumber="446"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// the sense of not + not, because doing so could result in values</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00447" /><CodeLine lineNumber="447"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// comparing</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00448" /><CodeLine lineNumber="448"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// as equal that hash differently in the min/max cases like:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00449" /><CodeLine lineNumber="449"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// select (cmp slt, X, Y), X, Y &lt;--&gt; select (not (not (cmp slt, X, Y))), X, Y</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00450" /><CodeLine lineNumber="450"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   ^ hashes as min                  ^ would not hash as min</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00451" /><CodeLine lineNumber="451"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// In the context of the EarlyCSE pass, however, such cases never reach</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00452" /><CodeLine lineNumber="452"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// this code, as we simplify the double-negation before hashing the second</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00453" /><CodeLine lineNumber="453"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// select (and so still succeed at CSEing them).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00454" /><CodeLine lineNumber="454"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordFlow">if</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> (LHSA == RHSB &amp;&amp; LHSB == RHSA) &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00639" /><CodeLine lineNumber="639"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// cases so that instcombine and other passes are more effective. It is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00640" /><CodeLine lineNumber="640"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// expected that a later pass of GVN will catch the interesting/hard cases.</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00658" /><CodeLine lineNumber="658"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A scoped hash table of the current values of all of our simple</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00659" /><CodeLine lineNumber="659"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// scalar expressions.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00660" /><CodeLine lineNumber="660"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00661" /><CodeLine lineNumber="661"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// As we walk down the domtree, we look to see if instructions are in this:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00662" /><CodeLine lineNumber="662"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// if so, we replace them with what we find, otherwise we insert them so</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// that dominated values can succeed in their lookup.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00664" /><CodeLine lineNumber="664" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-earlycse-cpp-/earlycse/#a1fdc6655978cda56c76b557d6d4d81e7"><span class="doxyHighlight">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-earlycse-cpp-/earlycse/#aba4b51f960b607643c1c0d4b3c103fd9">ScopedHTType</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/anonymous-namespace-earlycse-cpp-/earlycse/#a1fdc6655978cda56c76b557d6d4d81e7">AvailableValues</a>;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00665" /><CodeLine lineNumber="665"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00666" /><CodeLine lineNumber="666"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// A scoped hash table of the current values of previously encountered</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00667" /><CodeLine lineNumber="667"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// memory locations.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00668" /><CodeLine lineNumber="668"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00669" /><CodeLine lineNumber="669"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// This allows us to get efficient access to dominating loads or stores when</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00670" /><CodeLine lineNumber="670"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// we have a fully redundant load.  In addition to the most recent load, we</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// keep track of a generation count of the read, which is compared against</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the current generation count.  The current generation count is incremented</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// after every possibly writing memory operation, which ensures that we only</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// CSE loads with other loads that have no intervening store.  Ordering</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// events (such as fences or atomic instructions) increment the generation</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// count as well; essentially, we model these as writes to all possible</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// locations.  Note that atomic and/or volatile loads and stores can be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// present the table; it is the responsibility of the consumer to inspect</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// the atomicity/volatility if needed.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/anonymous-namespace-earlycse-cpp-/earlycse/loadvalue"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">struct </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/structs/anonymous-namespace-earlycse-cpp-/earlycse/loadvalue/#a20a42c6c09981e7a5e38494f3cfa1134">LoadValue</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01447" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1447"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// and we can forward values across it. For invariant starts without</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01448" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1448"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// invariant ends, we can use the fact that the invariantness never ends to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01449" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1449"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// start a scope in the current generaton which is true for all future</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01450" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1450"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// generations.  Also, we dont need to consume the last store since the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01451" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1451"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// semantics of invariant.start allow us to perform   DSE of the last</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01452" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1452"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// store, if there was a store following invariant.start. Consider:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01453" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1453"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01454" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1454"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// store 30, i8&#42; p</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01455" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1455"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// invariant.start(p)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01456" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1456"><span class="doxyHighlight">    </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// store 40, i8&#42; p</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01872" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1872"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A simple and fast domtree-based CSE pass.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01873" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1873"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01874" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1874"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This pass does a simple depth-first walk over the dominator tree,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01875" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1875"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// eliminating trivially redundant instructions and using instsimplify to</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01876" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1876"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// canonicalize things as it goes. It is intended to be fast and catch obvious</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1877"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// cases so that instcombine and other passes are more effective. It is</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01878" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1878"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// expected that a later pass of GVN will catch the interesting/hard cases.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1879"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">template</span><span class="doxyHighlight">&lt;</span><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">bool</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> UseMemorySSA&gt;</span></CodeLine>
